Food Bank of Alaska
August 25 at 4:21 PM ·

Do you or someone you know have school-aged children who were eligible for free or reduced priced school meals during the last school year? There is new program that can help with food assistance for families: Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT). Eligible families who receive SNAP will automatically receive these benefits, but families who do not receive SNAP will need to opt-in. Visit foodbankofalaska.org/pebt to learn more, or contact our Outreach team for assistance opting-in to this benefit by texting PEBT to 907-891-8913. ***NOTE - the deadline has been extended to September 30th, and we encourage families to apply by September 15th to ensure access to benefits.

shared_text:
Maniilaq Association
August 20 at 12:18 PM ·

Community transmission of COVID-19 is happening in the Northwest Arctic Borough. Maniilaq continues to offer testing at the airport or tent, but not everyone that travels to the region utilizes this opportunity. In order to flatten the curve, we all need to do our part, by making sure our guests and visitors are linked to COVID-19 testing. It is possible to be asymptomatic and contagious; this means that a person can feel fine but still be spreading COVID-19.

One way to help reduce the spread is to be vigilant and keep our social bubble small. The best way to reduce the spread is to wash hands frequently, clean high touch surfaces often, cover your cough and sneezes, travel only when necessary, and wear a mask in public places and when it's not possible to stay 6 feet away from non-household members.

Thank you to the people in Kotzebue who came to MHC today for a COVID-19 test. For those that were tested, please limit contact with others until you receive your test results in order to minimize possible spread.

We will strive to get results to those tested as soon as possible. Because of the number of samples gathered today and the lab staff needed to run the tests, results may not be available until tomorrow or Monday depending on the final number of tests. Thank you in advance for your patience while you’re waiting for results, but more importantly thank you for getting tested.

Testing will be available again on Monday, June 8th. Testing Center hours will be posted here on our Facebook page.

Congressman Don Young
May 16 at 12:39 PM ·

Congratulations to all Alaskan high schoolers graduating with the Class of 2020! This is a difficult time to be graduating, and I’m sorry you can’t physically be with your classmates, teachers, and family. You have accomplished great things, but these circumstances don’t detract from that. I wish you all the best in the future!

In the coming weeks, I will be sending Congressional certificates of recognition to graduating seniors. It might not completely make up for missing commencement ceremonies, but it is one small way for me to recognize high school students for their great accomplishments.

Parents and students may click here to sign up for a certificate: https://bit.ly/2Lyb7hT

shared_text:
Northwest Arctic Borough
May 19 at 5:09 PM ·

Northwest Arctic Borough Emergency Proclamation "Hunker Down" Amended & Extended, Order EO-02 in Response to COVID-19.

“Begins at 10:00pm on March 23, 2020 and remain in effect until 10:00pm on May 31, 2020.

Everyone currently in the Northwest Arctic Borough shall stay at home as much as possible, except to work in certain jobs.

On the limited occassions when individuals leave home, they should maintain social distancing of at least six feet from anyone outside their household whenever possible.

Individuals are also encouraged to practice recommended hygiene, including regular hand washing.

A Borough wide curfew will be in place from 12:01am until 6:00am. Only those reporting from certain critical jobs, listed in the order, will be exempt.”

Maniilaq Association
May 5 at 1:03 PM ·

Brittni and Indigo with Maniilaq Public Health Nursing demonstrate the process of screening and testing upon arrival into Kotzebue. For the past couple of weeks Maniilaq Association has been offering screening and rapid testing to incoming passengers and offering guidance on self-quarantining per the Northwest Arctic Borough and State of Alaska’s travel mandate.

It is important for the health of communities that individuals agree to voluntary testing upon arrival. That way if someone tests positive, the individual and others they have been in contact with can be isolated immediately, slowing the possible spread of disease in our region.

Regardless of being tested and receiving a negative result, passengers are still required to quarantine for 14 days after returning to the Maniilaq service area.

Remember to travel only if necessary to help keep our region healthy.

May 3 at 10:07 AM ·

This is a difficult year to be graduating from high school, with so much uncertainty swirling in our world and the inability to celebrate and gather in the same way as in years past. I wanted to take the opportunity to address our graduates, applaud them for their hard work, and remind them that, like certain past generations, our country is going to be looking to them to give their all as we come out of this crisis. To our graduates—we're very proud of you, Class of 2020. Here’s my message to you from a very special place in our nation’s capital.

Remind your children to not play out with people who are not living in their household.

Lets keep working together to keep our community safe.

Alaska Health and Social Services
April 10 at 6:11 AM ·

We know there's been a lot of interest in masks lately and parents, families and caregivers may be wondering what age a child should be in order to safely wear one.

Cloth face coverings should not be placed on children under age 2. It's very important that you never put a mask or face covering on an infant (or an adult) who is not able to adjust or remove the mask themselves. This could compromise their ability to breathe.

You can find more information about using face coverings to slow the spread of COVID-19 on the CDC’s website: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/diy-cloth-face-coverings.html

DHSS also has this webpage on face coverings: dhss.alaska.gov/dph/Epi/id/Pages/COVID-19/coveryourface.aspx

SOA April 9 COVID-19 Health Mandate 013: K-12 Public and Private Schools

Alaska Health and Social Services
April 9 at 5:35 PM ·

Today Governor Mike Dunleavy announced #COVID19 Health Mandate 013 which extends the closure of K-12 public & private schools through the end of the 2019-20 school year. Student learning will continue according to each school district’s plan using distance-delivered services. This mandate supersedes Health Mandate 008 which closed schools through May 1.

All school districts considering how to celebrate this year’s graduates need to follow the social distancing requirements outlined in COVID-19 Health Mandate 011 which prohibits gathering for events, including graduations.

Read the full Health Mandate 013 below:

post_text: Here's a video reading from the World Health Organization of a new book that can help kids better understand COVID-19 and how to protect themselves --with the guidance of a kind dragon named Arlo. Thank you, Maniilaq Association, for sharing.
shared_text:
World Health Organization (WHO)
April 9 at 4:49 AM ·

Kids, meet Ario - a kind, orange dragon with a horn like a unicorn, who will introduce you to COVID-19 and help you understand how to protect yourself, your families and friends from the coronavirus.

A new story book “My Hero is You, How kids can fight COVID-19!” - aimed at children aged 6-11 years old, is released today to help children understand and come to terms with COVID-19.
The story book also explains to children how to manage difficult emotions when confronted with a new and rapidly changing reality.

This book has been produced by a collaboration of more than 50 organizations working in the humanitarian sector, incl. WHO, UNICEF, UNHCR, the UN Refugee Agency, International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies and Save the Children US.

We are grateful to Howard Donald for giving the first public reading of this book “My Hero is You - how kids can fight COVID-19" in support of the "Read The World" initiative by the International Publishers Association, UNICEF & WHO.

Watch the reading on our YouTube - link in comment below!

shared_text:
GCI
March 20 at 8:05 AM ·

FREE Entry Level Internet until May 31

Right now, all Alaskans have a need for connection. That is why we are working to make a variety of connectivity options for our neighbors to help.

For existing customers, we have provided the option of a Free Upgrade to the next plan for any current GCI Internet customer through May 31. We want to give you even more connectivity in coming weeks.

We also want to ensure that all Alaskans are connected. So for those Alaskans who are not a GCI Internet customer we are now offering free entry-level Internet service until May 31, 2020. We want make sure all our students, families and loved ones all have a chance to be connected during this time.

We are all stronger when we are connected. For full details visit: www.gci.com/offers/free-internet

Maniilaq Association
March 4 at 6:00 PM ·

Maniilaq Health Center (MHC) strives to control the spread of communicable disease in our region but needs your help. Although 𝘁𝗵𝗲𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗻𝗼 𝗰𝗼𝗻𝗳𝗶𝗿𝗺𝗲𝗱 𝗖𝗢𝗩𝗜𝗗-𝟭𝟵 (𝗻𝗼𝘃𝗲𝗹 𝗰𝗼𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗮𝘃𝗶𝗿𝘂𝘀) 𝗰𝗮𝘀𝗲𝘀 𝗶𝗻 𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗴𝗶𝗼𝗻 𝗼𝗿 𝗶𝗻 𝗔𝗹𝗮𝘀𝗸𝗮, we are still in the midst of the cold & flu season.

With the upcoming 1A Regional Tournament hosted at Kotzebue High School this week we wanted to share ways you can protect yourself and those around you:

-Stay home if you are sick.
-Wash your hands thoroughly and often.
-Cough and sneeze into a tissue or your elbow.
-Avoid touching your eyes, nose and mouth.

Have a great weekend and best of luck to all teams competing!

shared_text:
Alaska Sports Hall of Fame
November 25, 2019 at 9:50 AM ·

Congratulations Spencer Woods on being named the ASHOF Alaska Athlete of the Week!

Spencer Woods of Shungnak qualified for the Olympic Trials in Greco-Roman wrestling by winning the silver medal at 170 pounds at the Bill Farrell Memorial in New York City. Woods, of Kotzebue High fame, is a former standout at the University of Maryland. Woods won four matches by a combined 24-6 score and was the top American in his weight. Earlier this month, Woods won a gold medal at the Malar Cupen in Sweden.

The Alaska Sports Hall of Fame Alaska Athlete of the Week is selected each Friday with the winner announced every Saturday at 11 a.m. on the Sports Guys on CBS Sports 590AM and 96.7FM.

Maryland Terrapins Kotzebue Huskies Shungnak School ASAA

post_text:
Students in Deering are currently in Nome participating in Alaska Humanities Forum's Sister School Exchange!

The Sister School Exchange program matches a teacher and five students from a rural system community with a teacher and five students from a more urban area in Alaska. These teams work through a 6-8 week curriculum on cross-cultural understanding, and then take turns visiting and hosting each other.

If you are interested in learning more about how the Sister School Exchange operates visit: https://www.akhf.org/sse

post_text:
This past weekend the Kotzebue DDF team (Debate, Drama, Speech Forensics) competed in the ASAA State Championship for the first time. The students participated in learning workshops, performed in competitive pieces, and even had the opportunity to go see a professional production of “The Sound of Music” at the Alaska Center for the Performing Arts in Anchorage! The students gave performances in pantomime, duet acting, and reader's theatre events.
Due to their positive attitudes, willingness to volunteer, and sense of friendship and comradery with teammates and opponents alike, the team was given the award for “Best Sportsmanship” in their division. We are very proud of these future leaders! #aklearns

Due to their positive attitudes, willingness to volunteer, and sense of friendship and comradery with teammates and opponents alike, the team was given the award for “Best Sportsmanship” in their division. We are very proud of these future leaders! #aklearns

post_text:
The Upriver Youth Leaders Retreat was a fantastic success. Students and staff spent three days on activities designed to help them combat substance abuse and the risk of suicide in their schools. Students involved in the Youth Leaders Program have made a commitment to act as leaders and advocates for their fellow students and will go on to serve as future leaders in their communities.

The retreat ended on an unexpected high point. The route of the Kobuk 440 ran near the camp and the students were able to cheer on three of the teams as they completed the Shungnak to Ambler stretch of the race.

post_text: There was a historic meeting March 21st 50 miles south of Shungnak. For the first time groups of students from Shungnak and Huslia meet at the Selawik Hot Springs. Although students from the NWABSD and Huslia regularly makes trips to the Hot Springs there has never been a coordinated effort to arrange a gathering before. Thanks to the efforts of Raymond Woods, bilingual coordinator for the NWABSD, the trip was a resounding success. We are already planning next years meeting and hope to make this an annual event.

post_text:
March Madness is over and the Northwest Arctic Borough has cause to celebrate. The district was represented at the State Championships by the Boys and Girls from Buckland, Selawik Girls and Noatak Boys in the 1A division, and the Kotzebue Girls in the 3A division.

The Noatak Lynx emerged as State Champions after battling it out with the Wolves of Nunamiut. This is the first championship for Noatak since 1988 and marks the end of a 27-1 season under the inspired leadership of coach Brianna Kirk.

The Lady Wolves of Selawik claimed State Runner-up after playing a neck and neck game against the Aniak Lady Halfbreeds.
